Implement voice-triggered prompt templates and adaptive dictionary for murmer. Read CLAUDE.md and README.md for context. The base dictation pipeline already works. Now add three new modules.

MODULE 1 - Prompt Template Modes in src/modes/

Create src/modes/mod.rs, src/modes/engine.rs, src/modes/extractor.rs, src/modes/context.rs, src/modes/registry.rs

A. Registry: Load mode definitions from config TOML. Each mode has a name, trigger phrases list, description, template string with slot placeholders, and optional output routing.

B. Engine: When dictation arrives, check if it starts with any trigger phrase. If matched, strip the trigger, pass remaining text through the slot extractor, fill the template, inject context variables, route the output. If no trigger matches, fall back to normal cleanup mode.

C. Extractor: Use the Ollama LLM to extract structured slots from casual speech. Given a template with named slots and raw dictation, ask the LLM to return JSON with slot values. Parse the JSON response. Also generate non-counting outcomes and failure modes when the template requests them via special slot names like generated_non_counting_outcomes or generated_failure_modes.

D. Context injection: Replace context variables in filled templates. Supported variables: clipboard via wl-paste or xclip -o, git_diff via git diff, git_staged via git diff --cached, last_output stored in memory from previous paste, file:path reads a file, shell:command runs a command and captures stdout. All context injection happens locally - no network calls.

E. Output routing: Default is paste at cursor. Also support clipboard only, file:path writes to file, exec:command pipes to stdin of command.

MODULE 2 - Adaptive Dictionary in src/dictionary/

Create src/dictionary/mod.rs, src/dictionary/store.rs, src/dictionary/learner.rs

A. Store: Persistent JSON file at ~/.local/share/murmer/dictionary.json. Contains static entries from config plus learned entries with frequency counts and confidence scores. Loads on startup, saves on change.

B. Static config entries come from config.toml under a dictionary section. Format: term = expansion.

C. Learner: After each transcription, scan for repeated short uppercase tokens or tokens that appear frequently but have no dictionary entry. Cross-reference against context sources like recent git log messages, file names in cwd, or clipboard history. When confidence is high enough threshold 3 occurrences plus context match, auto-add to dictionary. When uncertain, log a suggestion.

D. Integration with cleanup prompt: Before sending to LLM for cleanup, inject the dictionary into the system prompt as a vocabulary list the speaker uses these abbreviations followed by each entry.

MODULE 3 - Config extensions in src/config.rs

Extend the Config struct to include:
- modes: Vec of ModeConfig with name, triggers, template, output, description
- dictionary section with static entries HashMap and learning subsection with enabled bool and suggestion_threshold u32
- Add built-in default modes for loop, review, spec, fan, and command that are always available even without config

BUILT-IN DEFAULT MODES:

loop - triggers: loop this, ralph this, iterate on. Template extracts objective and success_condition, generates non_counting_outcomes, wraps in a persistence-gated brief with TASK, SUCCESS PREDICATE, DOES NOT COUNT, EFFORT, RETURN CONDITION sections.

review - triggers: review this, check this, audit. Template uses clipboard_or_git_diff context, extracts focus area, generates failure_modes, wraps in adversarial review brief.

spec - triggers: spec this, specify, make this precise. Takes raw dictation and asks LLM to output DEFINITIONS, TASK, DOES NOT COUNT, VERIFICATION, RETURN CONDITION structure.

fan - triggers: fan out, parallel, explore angles. Extracts objective, generates diverse approaches, wraps in parallel search orchestration brief.

command - triggers: translate, summarize, rewrite, explain. Direct passthrough of dictation to command-model LLM.

WIRING INTO MAIN:

Update src/main.rs process_recording function. After transcription and before LLM cleanup:
1. Load modes registry
2. Check if transcription matches any trigger
3. If yes: run through template engine instead of cleanup
4. If no: run through normal cleanup with dictionary-enhanced prompt

TESTING:

Write unit tests for:
- Mode registry loading from TOML config
- Trigger matching with prefix detection and case insensitivity
- Template slot filling with mock extractor responses
- Context variable replacement mocking shell commands
- Dictionary store load save and lookup
- Dictionary injection into cleanup prompts
- Frequency tracking in learner

Use mockito for any LLM calls in tests. Gate hardware-dependent tests behind cfg flags.

VERIFICATION after each phase:
cargo fmt
cargo clippy --no-default-features -- -D warnings
cargo test --no-default-features
cargo build --release --no-default-features

All must pass before moving to next module.

Output DONE only when all three modules are implemented with tests, all verification commands pass, and cargo build --release --no-default-features succeeds.
